COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 756, L.D. 1949
1 Sec. D-1. Environmental justice principles; report. The Public Utilities
2 Commission shall evaluate and identify ways in which the commission may incorporate
3 environmental justice principles into the performance of its duties.
4 For the purposes of this section, "environmental justice principles" means principles
5 that support protection from environmental pollution and the ability to live in and enjoy a
6 clean and healthy environment, regardless of race, color, national origin, class, ability,
7 gender identity, sexual orientation, ethnicity or ancestry, religious belief, English language
8 proficiency or income, which include the meaningful involvement of environmental justice
9 populations with respect to the development, implementation and enforcement of
10 environmental laws, rules, regulations and policies and the equitable distribution of energy,
11 health, economic and environmental benefits and energy, health, economic and
12 environmental burdens. For the purposes of this section, "environmental justice
13 population" means any census block group in which the annual median household income
14 is not more than 80% of the State's annual median household income; persons of color or
15 indigenous persons constitute 7% or more of the population, but the annual median
16 household income does not exceed 150% of the State's annual median household income;
17 or more than 1% of households are categorized as having limited English proficiency.
18 The commission shall submit a report to the Joint Standing Committee on Energy,
19 Utilities and Technology by February 15, 2026 with recommendations regarding the
20 incorporation of environmental justice principles into the performance of its duties. The
21 committee may report out a bill related to the commission's report to the Second Regular
22 Session of the 132nd Legislature.'
23 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
24 number to read consecutively.
25 SUMMARY
2266 This amendment does the following.
27 1. It changes the eligibility criteria for a residential customer who is protected from
28 disconnection by a public utility for nonpayment and limits the criteria to customers of a
29 transmission and distribution utility.
30 2. It removes the provisions of the bill addressing sales practices of competitive
31 electricity providers.
32 3. In the section of the bill establishing limitations on expenses that may be included
33 in a public utility's rates, it excepts certain consumer-owned utilities from the prohibition
34 on the inclusion in rates of contributions to a trade association, chamber of commerce or
35 public charity, including, but not limited to, a charity managed by the public utility or
36 affiliated interest. It removes the prohibition on the inclusion in rates compensation for an
37 employee of a public utility or an employee of an affiliated interest if any portion of that
38 compensation is used by the employee for lobbying or paid by that employee to a federal,
39 state or local government official in an effort to influence any official decisions of or
40 legislative decisions by the governmental official. It also defines "investor relations" and
41 establishes an exception to the prohibition on the inclusion of expenditures for investor
42 relations. The amendment also establishes a cap on the monthly costs that may be included
43 in rates associated with any contested rate case proceeding conducted before the Public
44 Utilities Commission in which the Office of the Public Advocate participated.
Page 5 - 132LR2159(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 756, L.D. 1949
1 4. It limits the provisions of the bill related to customer hardship reporting to
2 transmission and distribution utilities with over 50,000 customers and removes the
3 requirement that certain data be disaggregated by environmental justice population status.
4 5. It changes the date applicable to administrative charge proceedings conducted by the
5 commission to specify that the commission must initiate one or more proceedings by
6 December 31, 2025 as opposed to conducting one or more proceedings by December 31,
7 2025. It also limits the applicability of the proceeding to transmission and distribution
8 utilities with over 50,000 customers.
9 6. It removes the sections of the bill governing investor-owned transmission and
10 distribution utility customer bill requirements.
11 7. It removes the provisions of the bill enacting environmental justice requirements and
12 instead directs the commission to evaluate and identify ways in which the commission may
13 incorporate environmental justice principles into the performance of its duties. The
14 commission must provide a report to the Joint Standing Committee on Energy, Utilities and
15 Technology by February 15, 2026 with recommendations. The committee may report out
16 a bill related to the commission's report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd
17 Legislature.
